# Python Service Rules

## Architecture

```
services/segmentation-service/
├── app/
│   ├── main.py              ← FastAPI app entry, middleware, router registration
│   ├── config.py            ← Pydantic Settings (env-based config)
│   ├── api/                 ← Route handlers (thin — delegate to services)
│   ├── services/            ← Business logic and external integrations
│   ├── models/
│   │   └── schemas.py       ← Pydantic request/response models
│   └── core/                ← Shared utilities (auth, errors, logging)
├── tests/
│   ├── unit/
│   ├── integration/
│   └── conftest.py          ← Shared fixtures
├── requirements.txt
└── Dockerfile
```

## Scalability Patterns

- Use async/await for ALL I/O operations (httpx, database, file)
- Use background tasks or message queues for long-running inference jobs
- Never block the event loop with synchronous operations
- Use connection pooling for external services (httpx.AsyncClient)
- Implement health check endpoints: `/health` and `/health/ready`

## Code Quality

- Type hints on ALL function signatures
- Pydantic models for ALL request/response schemas — no raw dicts in API
- Use `pydantic-settings` for configuration (BaseSettings with env vars)
- Docstrings on public functions and classes
- Use `ruff` or `black` for formatting, `ruff` for linting

## Error Handling

- Use FastAPI HTTPException with detail dict: `{"code": "...", "message": "..."}`
- Catch and wrap external service errors (MONAI Label, MinIO)
- Return 503 Service Unavailable when MONAI Label is down (not 500)
- Log errors with context for debugging

## Testing

- Use `pytest` with `pytest-asyncio` for async tests
- Mock external services with `unittest.mock.patch`
- Test files: `test_*.py`
- Fixtures in `conftest.py`
- Minimum 80% coverage on business logic
